Parliament did not support an amendment to release Tymoshenko
Ukraine’s parliament has rejected a proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the penal code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the doors to the release of the former prime minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a disadvantageous agreement with Russia for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The sentence is not yet final, the appeals court has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code condemning the former prime minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
For its approval, 226 votes were required.
