“Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak comes to me, a Frenchman next to me says, ‘What, are you guys from the Visegrad Group?’
In the future, the EU, according to Vicenová, will face tough new budgetary policy rules for the Member States.
It is perceived as very real the concept of two speeds, if not more, in Europe, than the new "European Federation".
“We have countries in the eurozone and countries outside the eurozone.”
“We have the Schengen area and we also have the enhanced cooperation procedure.”
“It was said for the first time that only the countries that want to cooperate and those that don’t, that they stay out.”
“These procedures will become more and more and reinforce the two-speed Europe,” Vicenová is expected.
In this regard, he also highlighted the role of the Czech Republic and Herman van Rompuy in the application of the principle, according to which all issues affecting the entire EU should be discussed among member states, not only among members of the Eurozone.
Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were to look for a term that very precisely defined IBM’s strategy, the closest one would be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The foundation of this long-term character was laid by the firm’s first boss, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the slogan that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his label, around which the life of the giant future will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully constructed company culture.
“For us, IBM implies long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its core principles, but without fearing the changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to thrive even more in our second century,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current director.
