7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Missing Interview, Shown at a Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most telling, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off in anticipation of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a self-recognised designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flow chart junkie – a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringley was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds over the dawn of the personal computer, and sat down for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time, it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already hard at work at his new computer company NeXT, waiting for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used on Nerds, he said the interview originals disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly re-released footage is the basis for Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which hits Landmark theaters Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to lay out his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers – 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism surfaces, where he seems impatient due to Cringley's questions, pushing him to go faster toward the issues or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
On how you learned to run a business:
“Over the years in the business, I would always ask, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers they invariably give you are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting to great lengths.
Bewildered by the way costs were recorded – often starting with a “standard cost” that was made to look good, and then adjusted with a “variable” – he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
On the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make free long distance calls.
It’s been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here when describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world a half-dozen times and you’d yell through the pay phone and come back a minute later to the pay phone next door,” Jobs says with a chuckle.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us didn’t know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing – it was an amazing lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the U.S. diplomat, the two burst out in laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
On falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode-tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Soon in his career, as he set about selling a handful of motherboards, a customer asked him if he could assemble all the equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he remembers the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went outside and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble over his vision, and lose control of their market share.
“Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make photocopiers and printers better, so what?”
You have a monopoly of market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this class of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision-making.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position is rotted by people who do not have the notion of good products vs. bad products - the necessary knowledge of the trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product ... as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t get electrons to do, glass to do them, robots to do them, factories to do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - fit them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste - it comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, you might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
