How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each party accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired soccer coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “stuck” with an open microphone claiming US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his quickly refuted denials of the irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating in school and college exams are widespread.
There have been instances where teachers have given test responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that you can be lied to anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Sure, a lot of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or “finding lies,” is an essential skill that we all must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim, “I have you,” the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been refuted.
The liars look into the eyes.
They don’t always stutter, babble, blush, or fuss.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about statement structure, microfacial expressions, question formation, and timings.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detecting deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies," while women tell more "other-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their partners than people who are not married (but the lies they usually tell tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline."
It helps provide benchmarks for later measuring changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
You’d better know if someone normally taps your foot all the time so you don’t make unfair accusations when you see your feet tapping in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for deceptive, verbal, and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze their upper body by trying to remember their story, can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview release" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the tough questions are over.
Questioners often falsely pretend that the interview is over only to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the time passed while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman...Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... even as far as I know... as I understand."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to uncover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
