Cut validates "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed against the presidential decree that advances the so-called “analog blackout” from 2021 to 2015, by not meeting the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree that details the actions to follow to realize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft judgment, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favor of the project only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and upon admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it arranged for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister president said he does not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I also do not believe that doing so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector correspond to the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate, the rectory of the State.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, and results in better utilization of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the change, he said, would be postponing the benefits of digitization, which involves a decision in the public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he stressed, "demand the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic rectory of the State, encompasses a group of attributions that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the impugned decree, invades in some way the sphere of competence of the Congress, since it is providing in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he said.
They analyze the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data provided by the PREP, the difference between first and second place of the governor’s election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of "vote by vote" counting is a reality in terms of this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place of the governor's election is barely 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local norms with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Law, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period for them to enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted their publication within the deadlines provided for in the Law on the Official State Newspaper, on the grounds that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state president to constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them."
Interviewed about the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total recounts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may occur in the assumptions that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no act of scrutiny and computation in the file of the box or does not work in the possession of the president of the same; or, when there are errors or obvious alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received at all polling stations in the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate presumed to have won the election in question and the one who obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the representative of the party and/or coalition that nominated the second of the indicated candidates.
The total count of the vote may also be carried out if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the candidate allegedly winning and the one placed in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate was placed in second place, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of a partial count will be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is just 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
