The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president tomorrow to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put that country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italian Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to unveil a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and put the entire eurozone in danger.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present the president with the outcome of his talks with political parties in his bid to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well delineated," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must pass a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain battered confidence in Italy.
Underscoring pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability put the yield on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers' association Confindustria, told reporters after meeting Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were boosted considerably by the backing of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the technocrat-majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could trigger a devastating new attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a Monti failure would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women’s organizations.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
To bail out Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone’s current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before early elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist it should be made up of only technicians, an indication of their qualms about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
