Fujimori hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted Tuesday to a public hospital to be evaluated for loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including a tongue cancer for which he has been operated on four times and which is kept under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Channel N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said that he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated four times of cancer to the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which other pathologies have been added such as severe erosive gastritis, cyst of the pancreas, kidney stones, hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs, listed the doctor.
Fujimori has been serving time in the National Special Operations Directorate of the police since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political and commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propitious for the exchange of information on all that are the political issues between the two nations," according to the Presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that emerged when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultation to its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group composed of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has in force with the South American country, since January of this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of tax exchange agreements in order to leave the “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), formed by countries that did not implement all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004 that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The mustachioed plumber passes the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly over 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before has he fought in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives this month in stores around the world, has been designed from the beginning to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS portable system, which allows you to play in three dimensions without using glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy should work without glasses," said Omar Alvarez, Nintendo's head of specialized press in Spain, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Alvarez noted that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally intended for that support", since until now hits such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman has maintained that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Alvarez has claimed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook less skilled users.
Once passed, the most expert will be able to give a "second round" to the levels of play, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an “aggressive D” or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions to be able to overcome the different challenges and “not succumb to optical illusions”.
This incursion of Super Mario in the three dimensions also supposes the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that did not occur since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo winks at the followers of the saga and repeats the formula of the success of the previous installments, consisting of the mustache plumber will have to travel through platforms mined from dangers in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in the movements, environments, costumes and enemies and also a Luigi "playable".
Colom supports Portillo’s extradition to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced Tuesday that he has processed the extradition of former governor Alfonso Portillo to answer in the United States for the conspiracy to launder $70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to judge him there.
At a press conference, Colom said that his decision is due to the independence of the judicial and executive powers, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He said that during his term he “did not get his hands on” judicial decisions and processed all extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom did is an executive procedure after all judicial and constitutional instances were exhausted to prosecute the former president between 2000 and 2004.
According to decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once his legal status in Guatemala has been resolved and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of embezzlement of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk
The entity was born to prevent the fall in the marginality of children without training
The balance of the first 25 years of life of the social support entity Trinijove is important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have received help to overcome a difficult situation throughout this quarter of a century.
To this is added the hundred long jobs currently obtained for this social group.
The anniversary served yesterday to take stock in an event held in the old factory complex of Fabra i Coats attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was born in the neighborhood of Trinitat Vella in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little training, without work, with problems of dogradicion or in a situation of falling into marginality.
The celebration yesterday in Sant Andreu concentrated a large number of heads of entities and institutions that in these 25 years have collaborated with the association.
The varied political representation, in the middle of the electoral season, showed the unitary character of the work carried out by Trinijove.
Together with the president of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the event was attended by the former Minister of Socialist Education, Ernest Maragall, and the former deputy mayor and current ecosocialist councilor Ricard Gomà.
The current Minister of Social Welfare and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the general director of the social work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also attended the great hall of the Fabra i Coats.
Mas said that Trinijove was born in a very difficult time and that the current one is too, but added that the work done so far "is a good base."
The president set Trinijove as an example for knowing how to fight against bad circumstances and for giving hope to people in difficulties.
“The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does,” he said.
Evicted an squatted farm where macro-festivals were held
The invaders had taken over 11 of the 13 floors of the building, in Balmes, 51
The 12 occupants left the farm at noon yesterday without offering resistance
Everything seems to indicate that the nightmare lived by the residents of 51 Balmes Street has come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the property they occupied illegally, and where they organized macrofestas that despaired the neighborhood, by court order and without the need for a police intervention.
When the operation ended, the door lock was changed to prevent a repeat of the situation.
"From now on, there will be access control," the administrator said.
The squatters, who had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building - the rest are inhabited - took all the electrical installation and part of the water, in addition to painting the walls and leaving residues of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three floors were the scene of mass parties, which lasted up to two days and despaired the tenants.
Next to the building there is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat told Europa Press that since the building was occupied the business has fallen by 80%.
The owner of the discotheque points out that the invaders of the farm made it unfair competition, since they sold the glasses for three euros, while in the discotheque they are worth 10.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment venue had had to respond to neighborhood noise complaints, while, as she pointed out, the discomfort was not caused by the customers of the nightclub, but by the inhabitants of the squatted house and, above all, the attendees of the parties that were organized there, which had increased their frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to angry neighbors in the area.
The head of the nightclub explained that the inconvenience was so great that she even reached an agreement with the owner of the property and nine months ago she "forgives" him the rent.
The Urban Guard also confirmed that in recent weeks it had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the municipal group of the PP in the city council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had demanded last week "immediately dislodge the property to end the problems of coexistence and civility that produce the neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area."
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the building occupied, but over the last few months the squatters had been entering all the floors of the building and almost all the floors, and that in some there have even been robberies.
In this sense, he added that, "it is necessary to end impunity and be forceful against the incivism that has been generated on the farm."
Also yesterday, the Mossos evicted a building in Nou Barris.
At 1530 hours the police went to 35 Mont-ral Street, after receiving a call from a neighbour who had observed four people entering the building.
All four were arrested at the time.
Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond controversies about fees
The municipal competition on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, in the heyday of the now-defunct Barcelona Metropolitan Corporation (CMB), this administration printed some promotional passes for Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
Moreover, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York’s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was again placed, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented in the north-south axis but above (mountain) - below (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park results in this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with wild boars in the role of the Yogi bear.
These were until, in September, the city council convened a megacompetition composed of 16 contests for as many doors of access to Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of park, no doubt.
Either that or someone is trying to put doors in the field.
The question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it supposes of reflection on the city is the topic of conversation among all the architects of Barcelona.
It is almost already a recurring theme to be grasped when two members of this ancient caste of elect are recognized in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects think, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastal front "it becomes necessary" to debate about "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerdà, that of the green apples, has not been carried out.
"It should be noted that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things because of its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex”, says the architect, for whom the title “doors of Collserola” contains a “lexical trap”: we must not think of them “as the accesses to a park, but the delimitation of some areas where we have to act”.
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, calls the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers derived from the "uncertainty that it is nowadays to project the public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "his song of the swan".
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where it can be built.
"Limiting something is already fixing the next step," that is, its overstep.
“You have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the Metropolitan General Plan (PGM)] can give rise to real disasters.”
Closer to the question, Modol believes that, simplifying, the valley slope of Collserola "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, not", by a merely topographical issue.
Mòdol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "should not fall on deaf ears", although he appreciates the opportunity that the city council offers to his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe conduct that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubt" about whether it is this technical profile that must lead the multidisciplinary teams ("a success," he points out) that have had to be created: "Architects should be just a tool."
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives title to this piece is complex, because in the bases of the contest a global vision of Collserola is missing: "16 transversal competitions have been convened -he says- in the mountain-sea sense, but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole".
This causes, at least where appropriate, that you have chosen to participate in the 16 contests.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may clash in program and definition with that of the next door architect.
In his opinion, yes, the city council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, in all its extension, an area of equipment that would make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino pardons Jonah Larrazábal and goes free
After 72 days of rooting, the legal representative of Casino Red granted the brother of the mayor of Monterrey forgiveness of the process that followed him for alleged blackmail
After being imprisoned for 72 days, Manuel Jonas Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of Casino Red granted the pardon before the Second Criminal District Court, which follows a process of blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on Casino Royale, the owner of Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, made public a series of photographs and videos in which Manuel Jonas allegedly demanded the payment of an economic fee for the city council to allow the clandestine operation of the betting house.
After the public complaint, the State Attorney opened criminal proceedings against the brother of the PAN mayor and on September 2 he was arrested and detained for 30 days.
After four hours before Public Prosecutor 3 in Patrimonial Crimes, he was transferred to Casa de Arraigo 1, located in the Old Quarter of the state capital.
He remained there for the 49 days following the issuance of a second injunction after the Public Prosecutor’s Office dismissed the crimes of bribery and organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to the Cadereyta prison allegedly for blackmailing the owners of the Casino Red with one and a half million pesos; however, he only remained a few hours in the medium security prison since there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to follow the trial held in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, an arrest warrant was issued by the secretary of the Second Criminal District Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigations, enough evidence was found to determine Jonah’s guilt, such as the payment of 1.5 million pesos to the representatives of the bookmaker in exchange for allowing the operation of the bookmaker.
On Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went before the judge José Luis Pecina to request forgiveness for the brother of the royal mayor; so in the next few hours he could recover his freedom.
During the legal proceedings, the agent of the Public Ministry attached to the Court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and who of the partners of the bookmaker was the one who granted the forgiveness, although the lawyer tried to reserve the name.
On the basis of file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jonas Larrazábal and henceforth no claim may be filed in relation to the process that followed him; in addition, he will not be required to compensate for damage or punishment.
After the hearing with the legal representative of the bookmaker, at about 15:50, Larrazabal Bretón was ordered to be released immediately.
The secretary of the Court, Jorge Yánez, went to the jail of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonas that he has been legally forgiven and his file will be archived.
You will also be notified of the immediate release order issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Ministry of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter impacted directly on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"Elements that appear to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
It also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the staff.
In addition, he said that the investigations carried out in the impact area do not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In a search it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
“The helicopter’s design was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
For the moment, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results before possible; however, the investigation can last several months, even could reach a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff operated at cruising speed and that this happened in a soft ascending terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of normal cruise operation at impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out under the rules of visual flight, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM located conditions suitable to take off, as the aircraft advances towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico there were layers of cloudiness at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloud conditions the crew has sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced area:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways path.
The aircraft’s debris dispersal pattern allows us to assume that the helicopter hit the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the accident, no evidence of any kind of explosion or fire is revealed in the wreckage of the ship.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
Parts of the aircraft have been found during field work at an elevation of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disjointed along this route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the cordoned-off site, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security leads research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the "Genetics of Childhood and Adolescence Obesity" protocol, which will allow markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Especialidades of the Siglo XXI National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research, the population is invited to participate, whether or not it is entitled, go to the sports units participating in the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico West) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 children is met, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
On World Diabetes Day, November 14, he said that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and a family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure measurement, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (it seeks to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight there was also a dramatic rise," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for the markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in the genes that are associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, and doctors hand it over in writing to parents, who are told each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, that is, the greater consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the pavement were attended to, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate, the potholes could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
In his lecture A technological opinion of potholes, given in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, near 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The CF researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that make up the folder, he said, is bathed in asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, this allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If they were modified asphalt, they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, he added, a last layer called rolling folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it should have more mechanical strength than the asphalt binder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to have the appropriate thickness and must take care of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it greatly affects asphalt binder performance.
When the soil becomes wet, the water diffuses into the interior of the folder and is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear is the rolling film and only afterwards the asphalt binder is affected, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to at the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
