On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with non-competent or non-consenting persons.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
“In Canada, euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal.”
“Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal,” explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
Eighty-five percent of Canadians have already spoken out in favor of euthanasia, saying it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 survey by Angus Reid.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
As for people who have practiced assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that a process against them should not be initiated.
With regard to maintaining or interrupting a patient’s care, the situation is not as clear, the report’s authors say.
In addition, its recommendations suggest that the Criminal Code indicate that withdrawal from health care, if legally rejected, is not a criminal offence.
The expert committee also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses end-of-life care without fear of facing a complaint.
On palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cases of cancer.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered as euthanasia and undergo the same procedures.
Other experts have reservations.
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada’s expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, specialist in health law, has described as "extreme" the position of the experts who sign the report, among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill patients.
“This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over the age of 18 can ask for help to commit suicide,” Deschamps said.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value in society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, calling it a "pro-euthanasia manifesto."
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, especially calls into question the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
