Introducing a budget “golden rule” in the Constitution
Austria’s ruling Social Democratic/Christian Democratic Grand Coalition government decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a budget “golden rule” to reduce the government deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade of Austria’s sovereign rating rating by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a figure much higher than the maximum limit of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were reduced by a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay 3 billion euros more in interest each year,” said Christian Democratic Deputy Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responds to a request of the Brussels Summit to the member countries of the euro area on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in a Law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian government approximates the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, as of 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the regional states, as well as the communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is that, by 2020/2021, public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
