Energy policy:
Facts are worth more than dogmas.
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with considering short-term considerations or just thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is fitting that an election meeting is the time to reflect on such issues and the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will be useful only if it considers the full economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will mean the doubling of electricity demand before 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be alleviated to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case either in Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to cite a few examples, are moving forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, on the other hand, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a discourse.
The choice of Berlin will mean an increase in the price of electricity, a greater dependence on energy due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
Consideration should be given to the case of Denmark.
European champion in the wind sector, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would detract from the wonderful declarations about the reindustrialisation of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express opposition in principle to this type of energy, according to surveys.
Recall that the energy policy of our country has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and that can create non-relocatable jobs.
Should France decide to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of the 6 billion euros per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is scheduled to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of solutions with low CO2 emissions, nuclear and renewables, demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a Safety Authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of renowned professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it had no consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and to a cooperation between the safety authorities, French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While it is being studied by all the electric players who want to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to assume the leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to look for the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration: a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "human rights country" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France “needs no foreign talents, workers or waiters.”
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone by stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande merely includes banalities, indicating that co-development will solve the "problem of migration".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent paper summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and hurts employment.
Fears about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pushing for lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for domestic workers and exercise mainly professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anaesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the wages and employment of nationals.
Taking this into account, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows means a rise in long-term real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to public budgets on average over his or her lifetime.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the growth points he was missing "with his teeth".
Those teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think about a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this since, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that for democracy to triumph over its enemies, it would be enough to vote as directly as possible.
We know, from Napoleon the Little, that it was a matter of thought.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this respect, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
We must reflect on this ambivalence in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in a good way.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly way.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or an empty stop to the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to make blows, but a common exercise, in full right, quiet and continuous, of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to finish the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that bends to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We care about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty regains the helm of the European project.
Because only together can Europeans reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their futures through investment.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
So be it.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new deadlock.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to “make” republicans.
An interest-driven revolution would not be enough.
This lesson still applies.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe on a political level, a real European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let us make Europeans.
