From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about links between al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Links between the long-suspected al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) terrorist group and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already “has the certainty.”
“The way both organizations operate and the intelligence services’ reports show that they are cooperating,” he said, without elaborating.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the catwalks.
Kidnapped at a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were killed the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers especially captured the interest of researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is progress, but we should certainly wait for more formal evidence before discussing operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys outside financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "supports" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and discourses of Boko Haram or its operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has been pressing Abuja ever since to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as a community of enlightened people unworthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in Hausa, “Western education is a sin”) incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It is politicized and demands strict respect for Sharia law, while its militants throw themselves into the fight against the unholy central government.
The latter are primarily oriented to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and attacks on police stations multiplied.
Abuja’s reaction was, as usual, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in his lifetime, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect becomes radicalized and abandons its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed responsibility for an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and, later, another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuja, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations’ local headquarters becomes its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist hub in Africa, ranging from Mauritania to Somalia to Nigeria, is of concern to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Chebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to “share all the information.”
The World According to Republican Presidential Candidates
In relation to China, Iran and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete in simplicity and lack of knowledge.
Can a crisis-weakened America manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might think so.
For the past few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other candidates have increasingly made thunderous statements and shortcuts on foreign policy, traditionally a strong point for Republicans.
They spread slogans, often unfounded, about China, Iran, aid to Israel.
Mitt Romney, the best-placed candidate in the race for the “Grand Old Party” nomination, has threatened to take the Chinese to the WTO and denounce them “for manipulation of their currency,” a key issue in an America exasperated by the migration of entire fragments of its sector to Asia.
It doesn’t matter if that means an explosion of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate with a sophisticated view of foreign policy, almost chokes on an attitude that “overwhelms” emotions.
He has called for a firm but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, stuck in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
In the style of Reagan
Romney has also promised military intervention in Iran if sanctions fail to disrupt his nuclear program.
“If I get elected, I will stop Iran,” he boasted.
"If Obama gets re-elected, they'll have the bomb."
He also pledged to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to meet his obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second highest-ranked candidate, shows a shameful ignorance of such issues.
Recently, he urged countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing “attempts to develop nuclear capability,” apparently ignoring the fact that China already has the military atom since 1964.
Texas Gov. Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants to intervene in Iran, says he is willing to deploy the U.S. military to Mexico to fight drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
The differences are considerable with 2008 Republican nominee John McCain, a foreign policy heavyweight.
Opponents of the current president counter that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They remember that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to loosen the piston in the fight against terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of their naive dialogue with Iran, on the hasty departure of the “boys” from Iraq and on their misrepresentations in Libya, and label it weak.
But the attacks are not easy for them.
The population judges in a rather positive way the national security balance of Obama, which ended with Bin Laden.
From Iraq, he is wary of military interventions that lead to a sinking.
And, arguing that it takes rebuilding America economically to resurrect its leadership, Obama gives the impression of being fairer.
Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic coast, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that directly connects, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and their Netherlands counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding the terrestrial passage by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All at once, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close off its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, given that the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has succeeded, in just five years, in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us in an organic way,” Francois Fillon confirmed during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of steel coated with cement to protect it against the anchors of ships.
It rests at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them as a precaution,” said Jens Muller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but those responsible for the project gave it up, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned company to permanently settle in the sea off its coast.
“In the event of a fault, we will interrupt the gas flow in less than a minute,” says Jens Muller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders are unlikely to see a leak, as they have forecast leaks every 100,000 years.
Control of the condition of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
With the shape of a cigar, it is introduced into the interior of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to run for fifty years without any repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the stakes.
It was joined by Germany’s E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Netherlands’ Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transmission capacity to Gazprom for a renewable period of 25 years.
“Gazprom will be paid for the full capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” says Jens Muller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out 30% with the contribution of shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that they will not outstrip their investment, as Gazprom bears the expense risk on its own.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back their love of writing.
It has an air of adventure, from hours of writing to the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a notebook of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the sidewalks.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Away is the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-spirited and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees in its beginnings, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city center, and has managed to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer cases ... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in the autumn of 2006, Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
“No,” says Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
“The progress made over the last 15 years is significant.
“Back then, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
“However, there is still a lot to do.”
It is worth mentioning that disabled unemployed persons continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that “constitute the crux of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of the people advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité pointed out that the directors surveyed have “a low level of knowledge about disabilities”, with an “excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually deficient”.
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“We now reach around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body in charge of collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated a lot of pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
Hazard: "A joy"
About to face the Bleus on Tuesday night (20:45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens do not hide the pleasure generated by this friendly match.
We dare not say that there was connivance between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side on the Stade de France auditorium stand, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made peace.
Five months after his striker’s grudge against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise for him.
"I was very happy for Eden, for his progress and for being Belgian."
"I want to move forward," the Lille forward responds.
As for the contrast between his presentations in his team and in the selection, "it is a set", it has been justified.
“In Lille, I’m all year, which doesn’t apply to Belgium.
"I have to stand up."
Called to play against Romania on Friday night, taking into account this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally "glow up".
Not to mention "pleasure."
He has been cheering for the Bleus since he was seven years old, as well as during the winning campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
“I’ve always been a fan,” he says.
This will certainly reinforce the "particular" character of the meeting.
Especially since he will face “Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami),” he recalls.
“We just faced each other recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy."
With simplicity, Leekens has made reference to "pride".
"Pride" for playing "a gala match".
"Pride" also for checking, as "neighbor", that France "returns to a team of very high level", about a year after the trauma of Knysna.
“Laurent Blanc has done a formidable job,” he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the coach would be delighted to be able to share a plane with the Bleus towards... Brazil, in 2014.
“Our little Belgians are growing up,” he said.
“We’re building something; the players are ambitious, they’re hungry.
"They'll be able to see him in the next matches." Including the match against France.
Portugal shows a lot of confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal are facing with great optimism the return match against Bosnia (22h00), which will be held on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked realism.
“When these 90 minutes pass, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country.”
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
There’s no doubt about it; Selecca, which he has been running since September 2010, is going to qualify for Euro 2012.
In fact, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there is a match to be played and a rival, Bosnia, to be defeated.
Considering the first leg (0-0), Friday in Zenica’s inferno, it seems clear that the matter is not decided.
Portugal dominated the game for more than an hour, yes, but could not score the valuable goal that would have given him peace of mind.
“It’s a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven’t scored away from home.”
But at home, in Lisbon’s luminous Estadio de la Luz, the Portuguese are convinced that they will pass, before an audience that should be just as excited, even if it is evident that the match “is very even”, said an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We expect the match to be very even, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead," the 42-year-old Portuguese coach said.
"We still have a 50% chance of participating in Euro 2012," said Carlos Queiroz's successor.
Friday’s draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
The Bosnians could get a draw, though they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we have not scored away from home," regrets Bento.
"We're going to play against a team that has a great technical quality and that has players with a great individual quality," he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting, from the beginning, maximum pressure on the Bosnians to "leave them no time to think".
A good idea, as long as, this time, it's realistic.
